description.plain:
Lauded for his vivid stories and proficiency on the mic, Jeremie Damon Pennick (b. November 27, 1984), best known as Benny The Butcher, is a rapper from East Side Buffalo, New York.

Associated with Griselda Records, which he officially became part of in 2016, Benny draws most of his inspiration from the New York rap scene of the 90s. Like his collaborators (and first-cousins) Westside Gunn and Conway The Machine, Benny cites Rakim, Nas, Father MC, JAY-Z, Mobb Deep, and Wu-Tang Clan as major influences.

Benny started rapping in 1999 as part of the group Killer Brown, which he had formed with his high school friends. In 2003, his career was cut short after he was charged with false identification and sent to federal prison. While serving his sentence, Benny competed in rap battles and cyphers with the other inmates. After he was released, Benny adopted the moniker “B.E.N.N.Y."—an acronym for "Best Ever ‘N New York"—and released his debut mixtape Tana Talk in 2004.

Benny continued self-releasing projects regularly, but he only took off at a local level with releases such as Tana Talk 2, The Mayor’s Back, and Benny Montana. For a short period, he also went by the name “2 Chain Bennymane,” but ultimately changed back. He would eventually settle on Benny The Butcher—at times capitalized as a callback to his original name.

At the start of the 2010s, Benny’s rap career was stifled once more with a two-year bid in prison for a probation violation. He decided to solely focus on music once released and co-founded the label Black Soprano Family in 2012 along with his manager. After steadily releasing material, Benny finally earned commercial and critical attention through a streak of increasingly successful projects, including 2018’s Tana Talk 3 and 2019’s The Plugs I Met.

In October 2020, Benny dropped his sophomore studio album, Burden of Proof, which featured high-profile production from Hit-Boy. Despite branching out from his gritty boom-bap sound, Benny received critical acclaim for pushing his boundaries.

It took just five months for Benny to return with an EP, The Plugs I Met 2, which dealt with the repercussions of street life and was executively produced by Harry Fraud.

Benny’s highly-anticipated third studio album, Tana Talk 4, dropped on March 11, 2022. It was preceded by the J. Cole-assisted single, “Johnny P’s Caddy,” which became Benny’s first entry on the Billboard Hot 100.

songs.full_title: Crowns For Kings by Benny the Butcher (Ft. Black Thought)
songs.title: Crowns For Kings

description.plain: The first song off The Plugs I Met, “Crowns For Kings” finds Benny The Butcher swapping verses with Black Thought over an up-beat DJ Shay-produced instrumental, which samples Al Green’s 1972 song “Look What You Done for Me.”  Benny raps about familiar topics, such as his come up in the rap game, his experience drug dealing, and his longtime success as a rapper.

songs.lyrics:
Crowns For Kings Lyrics[Intro: Benny the Butcher]
Uh, every king will be crowned
Trust me
Uh

[Verse 1: Benny the Butcher]
This marathon shit, so let's see who first to the finish
If it's less than a hundred racks, it don't deserve your attention
'Cause burdens come with it, my second test was servin' a sentence
My first was make a brick jump like it was hurdlin' fences
Certainly, my last shit was a courtesy, nigga
And further, we had bustdowns before you heard of me, nigga
Shoeboxes stacked with racks sittin' vertically in 'em
I'm fresh out of luck, I'm here 'cause I deserve to be, nigga
I sat back, a vet, and watched beginners winnin' my belts
Burned my bridges, came back a good swimmer like Phelps
You know the feeling, young black male, what y'all dealin'?
Take your whole life to get it, it only last you a minute
In the kitchen countin' cash with cats with backward agendas
Put a Benz in the brick, then toss it back in the blender
That was us, next to a big like I was Puff
The good die young, all the OGs thirty and up
In Alexander McQueen kicks just to dirty 'em up
Money tree, branches break when they not sturdy enough, uh
See, I was good with the bad guy role
Water in my jewels, put 'em on and baptize hoes
Walk in my shoes, we got Shaq-sized soles (Huh)
We flatline those wack rap niggas wearin' half-sized clothes
What's the dealy? I'm only 'bout six hours from Philly
That's an hour on the plane, I'll make it three in the Bentley
My bitch keep sayin' I'm famous, but it ain't hit me
I'm too ghetto, mellowed out, this Hollywood shit tricky
See, before I knew an A&R, I was weighin' hard
Back when Nicki Minaj was in a trainin' bra
You play this game, you better play it hard
The judge'll give you life and later that day, he gon' be playin' golf
I'm from that era, we don't pay it if you weighed it wrong
Back when your parents got your baby shoes plated bronze
We took hip-hop and made it ours
I sold quarters, just so happens I'm the author of your favorite songs
They bullshitted me, I played along
More bars than them niggas who got hit with the Reagan laws
Let's go
[Verse 2: Black Thought]
Yo, when we was hooked in the hood, gettin' booked like literature
Kept us shook, like when the boogieman comin' to get ya
We was crooks, tryna cop more rides than Great Adventure
Any image we took, not a father was in the picture
There was times, not a bite nor swallow was in the kitchen
Real niggas made a industry out of they intuition
Facin' the darkest outcome, sprintin' to outrun the reaper
Trying not to be the food in the mouth of the beast
For whom the bell tolls
Crown kings in Adidas suits and shell toes
We had to throw a lot of body blows and elbows
Wishin' we could get from Snyder Ave to Melrose
Without the Dapper Dan bodybags and jail clothes
That warned niggas not to lollygag when Hell rose
We railroaded through the thicker things for gold chains and chicken change
No one throwin' flames, there's growin' pains when in the game
And the blow, ashes in the snow, it's no remains
Push the wheel as fast as it could go, we overcame the obstacles
But when you official, the block miss you
Even if the old crew choose not to rock with you
We was blue-black, stuck in the glue trap
I had to pull my own self up by the bootstrap
Where everybody play they own part like a tooth gap
And old heads teach the young hitters to shoot back
I been livin' proof that the pressure make precious stones
And real Clarence Avants remain lesser known
But anybody who question you, send a message to 'em
I see my seat at the table to be a blessed throne
Triumph and tragedy, his majesty muscle never atrophied
The devil is a casualty, sucker, you're never catchin' me
Even though you been after me, motherfucker
You gotta bring a army to harm me, I occupy the capacity up
Decapitator of a hater in this modern day
My dossier no less, dealer spray Courvoisier
I'm Jean-Paul Gaultier, Tom Ford, and Cartier
Self-made, I fly vintage from the sommelier
On reserve, flowin' from the blackest fountain
It's all love from public housin' to the Atlas Mountains
I've established the average to always bat a thousand
So after butcherin' this track, it's back to countin'
The money generated from me leavin' microphones broke
Probably almost on par with all of Escobar's coke
When I'm finished, I'ma keep a tennis shoe on y'all throat
Just in case you mention in a interview you want smoke, nigga
Two FifteenYou might also like13Embed

description.plain: “Sunday School” finds Benny the Butcher alongside fellow Upstate New York rapper 38 Spesh and Jadakiss to deliver a braggadocios banger about drug dealing and the street life. The track features a menacing piano-based instrumental produced by Griselda’s in-house producer Daringer.

body.plain: “Sunday School” finds Benny the Butcher alongside fellow Upstate New York rapper 38 Spesh and Jadakiss to deliver a braggadocios banger about drug dealing and the street life. The track features a menacing piano-based instrumental produced by Griselda’s in-house producer Daringer.

songs.title: Timeless

description.plain:
A new Benny The Butcher and Lil Wayne collaboration has surfaced online called “Live Forever“.

This Hit-Boy-produced song is rumored to appear on the Griselda rapper’s forthcoming album, Burden Of Proof, which currently has no release date.

When listening to “Live Forever”, there seems to be a third verse missing, so there might be another music artist featured on the track when it is released officially.

description.plain: A track from Benny the Butcher’s debut album finds him reminiscing on his early days growing up on Montana Ave. Backed by the hard hitting beat provided by The Alchemist, Benny talks about his experiences on the streets selling drugs as well as the death of his older brother.

songs.full_title: 10 More Commandments by Benny the Butcher (Ft. Diddy)
songs.title: 10 More Commandments

description.plain:
The title off the track pays homage to the late Notorious B.I.G. and his song “10 Crack Commandments.” Benny further explained the song’s title and meaning in an interview with The Breakfast Club.

https://youtu.be/12TzbRvgURw?t=963

The track features an outro from Diddy, talking about black culture and legal hustling. Diddy himself was a close friend of Notorious B.I.G. and helped shape the album the original Biggie cut landed on.

On March 8, 2022, cousin Westside Gunn stated on Instagram that this song would be the second single to the album, saying quote:

I know we’re making ChineGun proud on this one, first single was with @realcoleworld and the next one “10 More Crack Commandments” is with @diddy and @djpremier just Classic Shit…

However, plans were likely changed ever since, as the track ended up being released just as an album cut. Nevertheless, the official music video was released on March 11, 2022, the same day as Tana Talk 4 came out.

Ten more crack commandments, ah
[Outro: Diddy]
Yeah-yeah-yeah-yeah, yeah-yeah, yeah-yeah
Check this out, it's all in the mindset, you know
It's all in the mindset

description.plain:
“Buffalo Freestyle” is an unreleased collaboration between Benny The Butcher and Drake, that was first previewed by Benny at Lyrical Lemonade’s Summer Smash on August 22, 2021.

songs.artist_names: Benny the Butcher (Ft. Stove God Cooks)
songs.full_title: Back 2x by Benny the Butcher (Ft. Stove God Cooks)
songs.title: Back 2x

description.plain:
Collaborating with fellow coke rapper Stove God Cooks for the first time, on ‘'Back 2x’‘, Benny throws out one-liners about his current spot in the rap game and his hustling days.

With ‘'Johnny P’s Caddy’' being a single, this track functions as the first new material we get to hear from Benny’s anticipated third studio album Tana Talk 4. This way, the song’s subject matter of Benny ‘'being back’‘ after his two-year album hiatus (which is a lot for Griselda’s consistency) fits perfectly into the album.

Even prior to release, the song was one of the most anticipated records off the album with Benny going on Instagram Live and playing the track in December of 2021.

songs.full_title: Sly Green by Benny the Butcher
songs.title: Sly Green

description.plain:
The song is titled after American gang leader Donald “Sly” Green, founder of the L.A. Boys gang in Buffalo, New York, which was the most powerful crime organization of the city from the 1980s to the first half of the 1990s. In 1994, he was sentenced to four life sentences for murders, RICO, drug dealing, kidnapping, extortion, conspiracy, and continuing criminal enterprise.

Griselda’s founder, Benny’s cousin, Westside Gunn was locked up with Sly and talked about him in multiple interviews.




Sly Green and Westside Gunn posing in their jail jumpsuits.

annotatable.title: Intro: Babs

body.plain:
To kick off his full-length debut with Griselda, the Butcher pays tribute to his hometown of Buffalo, New York.

The song is also named after his mother, Babs.

description.plain: Guerrero is the tenth track on Tana Talk 4 and features Benny’s frequent collaborator, cousin and one of the people on the cover, Westside Gunn. The track features some of the songs names from Benny The Butcher’s last two studio albums, Tana Talk 3 and Burden of Proof, in the context of his coke-rap attitude.

songs.title_with_featured: Tyson vs. Ali (Ft. Conway the Machine)

description.plain:
In “Tyson vs. Ali”, Benny The Butcher enlists his most frequent collaborator and member of Griselda, Conway The Machine.

The title refers to the great debate of who of the two best boxers in the world is capable of winning in a boxing battle, who are Mike Tyson and the late Muhammad Ali, who is Tyson’s idol and kept his promise to avenge his defeat to Larry Holmes in 1988, with a win for Tyson by a unanimous decision.

songs.full_title: Billy Joe by Benny the Butcher
songs.title: Billy Joe

description.plain:
“Billy Joe” is the ninth track from Benny’s Tana Talk 4.

On it, Benny discusses his reputation as a drug dealer and also speaks on his upbringing, examining the reasons why people resort to drug dealing. He has a sense of regret in regards to the drug game but he also comes off as proud of his own success that came from drug dealing.

body.plain: “Langfield” is a tribute to Benny’s murdered brother Machine Gun Black, who is painted on the artwork of the album. Over a Daringer-produced beat, Benny speaks directly to his brother and also reflects on how his death affected him and his family.

songs.lyrics:
Langfield Lyrics[Intro]
It’s real shit, nigga
I’m a A1 nigga, everything about me authentic
Uh, I came a long way, straight out the mud
From the bottom, I’m a real street nigga

[Verse]
Yo, sometimes a nigga feel like y’all deaf
I put my life in these songs and still feel like y’all slept
Every word I spoke in the booth, y’all know it’s the truth
It’s Benny, I’m firm as a soldier boots, spill my pain all over these loops
I know you resting, but you left me, bruh, your mom dukes especially hurt
This the shit that you try to protect us from
Having thoughts of you kept me up
I used to have dreams that the niggas that got at you would tried to wet me up
Uh, I never been the same since my brother died
On the prison phone, through the static, heard my mother cry
And I gotta call her back ‘cause people on the other line
Niggas came from busting nines and we don’t know from which side
Wait, take a minute, imagine that
When your whole crew strapped and y'all don’t know who to clap
Uh, niggas shook ‘cause they know how we gon’ react
So when we call to see what’s popping, they ain't answering they jacks
Was a orphan, streets adopted me, but they gave me back
Was a ‘80s baby, momma raised me, she was slanging crack
Foggy memories, okay, I’m thinking, let me take you back
I remember clear as day, when I caught her shaving crack
Had a boyfriend from Detroit, they took trips, made it back
Around that time, we used to cop the newest kicks, latest hats
Times change, fast forward, she a smoker, ain’t adapt
To the harsh ways of the game and it’s plain as that
I don’t blame her, but that’s probably why this the way I act
I just wanna stack this money, fuck these bitches, fade to black
If they ask me if I’m real, you just play ‘em that
When I die, just load up all my classics, play 'em back
Haters still in denial but the streets say I’m next
One of the hardest niggas out, at least let’s agree on that
We put the G in GFxR, Con, me, and West and diesel
Fuck being humble ‘cause we the best, uhYou might also like1Embed

songs.full_title: Welcome To The States by Benny the Butcher
songs.title: Welcome To The States

description.plain:
Benny hops on the beat of We Cry Together, off Kendrick Lamar’s recent album Mr. Morale & The Big Steppers, which was produced by frequent Griselda collaborator The Alchemist.

Welcome To The States addresses the tragic mass shooting that took place in Benny’s hometown of Buffalo on May 16 2022. All proceeds from the song are donated to the “Buffalo Survivors Fund”, which pays out all of its proceeds to survivors and victims of the shootings.

songs.lyrics:
Welcome To The States Lyrics[Verse]

Do this crazy white boy in his trench coat got a Ruger under?

'Cause the suits that vote on these laws don't deal with our challenges

And frankly, it made me look at my country a little bit stranger
Mass shooting in my city, eight minutes from where my block at

Y'all using that to antagonize rappers? I never got that
Before them CNN and Fox chats, explain to me where was y'all at?

[Outro]
Let me say a word about yesterday's mass shooting in Buffalo, New York. I've been receiving updates from my team at the White House that's in close contact with the Justice Department.  We're still gathering the facts, but already the Justice Department has stated publicly that it is investigating the matter as a hate crime, a racially motivated act of white supremacy and violent extremism
As they do, we must all work together to address the hate that remains a stain on the soul of America. Our hearts are heavy once again, but our resolve must never, ever waver

55 a gram, sell 'em for 90, that’s 20 cash
I ain’t really need the paper, I looked at it as a favor

I pulled the pound off my hip, put one in the head
Anybody still there when I come in, they dead

Last time I checked, the stash in the wall was 50

I got some more bad news just to add to the problem
The one that owe me locked in jail, that's why I can’t find him
It’s bad timing, and that’s gonna hurt me
Down to my last 10, and I owe him 30
Truthfully, what would you do if you was me?
I took a bigger loss, ain’t like I bought jewels and sneaks
I know the rules of the hood, I don’t abuse the streets
And I accept the consequences if I choose to cheat
I took mine and laid low and kept goons with me
That’s how a day on the East Side usually be, ahhh

I see pictures on the wall, Bible on the coffee table
Bible on the coffee table
I see pictures on the wall, Bible on the coffee table
Bible on the coffee table
I don’t regret it, no, I don’t regret it
Hard decisions had to be made to get to where I’m headed
Some niggas want the fame, some niggas want the credit
The streets will eat you alive but only if you let it

[Verse 2]
I see pictures on the wall, Bible on the coffee table
I pray my next deal put a meal across the table
Drinkin’ champagne, sittin’ at the bosses’ table
Gotta grind before you shine, nigga, that’s the laws of nature
I see pictures on the wall, Bible on the coffee table
Looked Judas in his eye, like, you gon’ cross us, ain’t you?

description.plain:
This is the original version to Back 2x off Benny’s third studio album Tana Talk 4.

This version of the song was played during an Instagram Live. It features a pre-chorus by Benny which the released version doesn’t have as well as mixing and production changes.
